{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c79bce67-6e72-46d6-b3b2-249cc425c3ea","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.x dropped the VSTest adapter entirely.** It now ships exclusively with Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) as the runner. Since `vstest.console` relies on the legacy VSTest adapter DLLs to discover tests, it finds nothing.\n\n### Your options:\n\n1. **Migrate your CI to use `dotnet test`** (recommended) — .NET SDK 9+ natively supports MTP, and .NET 8 works with `dotnet test` via the MTP bridge that MSTest.Sdk 4.x wires up automatically.\n\n2. **Re-enable the VSTest adapter bridge** if you must keep `vstest.console`:\n\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <EnableVSTestAdapter>true</EnableVSTestAdapter>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n   This restores the adapter shim so `vstest.console` can discover and run tests again.\n\n### TL;DR\n\n| SDK version | Default runner | vstest.console works? |\n|---|---|---|\n| 3.8.0 | VSTest + MTP | ✅ |\n| 4.1.0 | MTP only | ❌ (unless you opt back in) |\n\nThe simplest long-term fix is to replace `vstest.console` with `dotnet test` in your pipeline.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"946f797a-6cf8-4839-a6b4-8e7f0863891d","outputTokens":314,"requestId":"4813:1B7094:6625F2D:6E9A8B0:69FC0207"},"id":"3f2a2576-6594-4011-a508-2cb800d0bc92","timestamp":"2026-05-07T03:07:59.608Z","parentId":"6f7f1e93-2319-41f2-83f9-df41bb65250b"}
